Escape: "Every female refugee has had experiences of sexual violence"
Sexual violence is almost a part of everyday life for women who flee alone.
When they arrive in Germany, they are often traumatized.
A house is a place of refuge.
There are four women in a large kitchen.
Each carries a baby, one year old at the most.
One of them put her little boy in her arms.
He looks curiously into the room with big eyes.
His mother is staring at the table.
Until she realizes she's being watched.
She smiles and kisses the little one.
The scene seems normal.
Until they talk to Katrin Bahr.
She is the Managing Director of Condrobs, a social welfare organisation in Bavaria, and deals with the issue of women on the run.
The four women in the kitchen are refugees.
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralised accommodation for single women refugees and their children in Bavaria.
In January, Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and the Munich Women's Aid.
It was officially opened recently.
There are 60 people living there - about 40 women and 20 children.
There are no men - not even as visitors.
The exception is a guard at the door.
"It is no exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has experienced sexual violence on the run", says Bahr.
"Men flee wars because of political persecution, because they are threatened with torture or death, or because their families send them to Europe as bearers of hope", she says.
For women, other reasons predominate: "Many people sneak away because they see no other way out".
In their home country, they have experienced sexual violence, forced prostitution, honor killings, slavery, or forced prostitution.
That's what drives them.
It's still going on on the run.
"It is not uncommon for traffickers to demand sexual intercourse for a bottle of water", says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they are not protected by their families.
Whoever thinks that the end will come when they arrive in Germany is deluded, Bahr tells us.
Here too, single women in refugee camps were often treated as inferior and, in the worst case, abused.
This results in about 90 percent of the women living in the shelter in northern Munich being traumatized, she estimates.
"I'm sure some of the children were not born of their own free will".
Many women are so used to it that they don't say anything.
"Or they don't dare to talk about their experience openly because the shame is too great".
Since they often cannot help themselves, more accommodation is needed just for them, Bahr demands.
In Bavaria, the seven district governments are responsible for the accommodation of refugees.
When asked whether they knew of a similar project in their area of competence as in Munich, some would answer no.
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia, for example, there is no such thing in government accommodation.
Even in Swabia, women who have fled alone are not housed separately, says Karl-Heinz Meyer, a government spokesman.
In Upper Bavaria, Lower and Middle Franconia, some communal housing units have floors or separate houses for single women and their children only.
The exception is Lower Bavaria, where there are two central accommodation centres exclusively for women.
The Committee on Women's Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament also calls for women to be housed separately from men.
A study published for the committee states: "It is very important that men and women be housed separately".
"If there is no privacy or if men and women are housed together, there can be - continuing - violence against women".
In particular, the bathrooms should be separate and easily accessible to women, says the study.
The extent to which women feel this need for protection can be seen from the pressure on the house in Munich.
"Since we were first mentioned, we've had a long waiting list", says Bahr.
You could easily open a second house.
