The Depressing Food of the Economic Crisis in "A Plentiful Meal"
In March 1933, shortly after his ascension to the presidency, Franklin Delano Roosevelt had his lunch in the Oval Office.
As a foodie, President Roosevelt had a penchant for refined Fifth Avenue delicacies like pate de foie gras and Maryland water turtle soup.
His menu that day was a little more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and a plum pudding for dessert.
"It was an act of culinary solidarity with suffering people", Jane Ziegelman said.
Her husband Andrew Coe added, "It was also a message to Americans about how they should eat".
The couple live in Brooklyn Heights and are both food historians.
Coe's last book, "Chop Suey", was about Chinese cuisine in the United States, while Ziegelman's book, "97 Orchard", tells of life in a Lower East Side apartment building from a food perspective.
Their latest collaboration, "A Decent Meal", which will be published Tuesday in Harper's, illustrates the history of American cuisine during the Great Depression.
They showed culinary solidarity when they met with a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a small, no-nonsense snack in the Flatiron District that has been in business since the 1929 stock market crash.
Ziegelman, 54, ordered a fresh cheese sandwich with olive slices, while Coe, 57, ate turkey with mashed potatoes and vegetable mix.
When the reporter ordered a roast beef, the couple found it fitting for a discussion of food during the Great Depression.
"Friendly foods were very popular", Ziegelman said.
There was peanut bread, liver cheese, and bean bread.
They're made from one ingredient and something cheap that stretches the ingredient.
Imagine eating so many peanuts that they serve them as dinner.
Coe grinned.
"It must have settled in the stomach like lead", he said.
In the years before the Great Depression, the table in an American household, especially in rural areas, was an all-you-can-eat buffet.
Teams of women cooked for male field workers, and freshly baked pastries were served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. "A Square Meal" chronicles the ways in which the country dealt with the fact that it was no longer the land of the razor-sharp.
"It was a time when food became a central, tense topic for Americans", Coe began, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about it.
The new budget diet was just as tense: Mysterious foods like bread and casseroles became staples, which casseroles were "a wonderful way to recycle leftovers", Ziegelman noted, as chefs could hide unappetizing ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit was replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, which for years was the centerpiece of American cuisine, became a rarely served luxury.
Peculiar blends were tried, as a high-calorie and nutritious satisfaction took precedence over taste or even healthy cooking sensibilities.
During her research for the book, which also includes recipes, Ziegelman prepared a dish from that era, baked onions with peanut butter.
"It was not a popular addition to the lunch", says Coe.
Ziegelmann continues: "It was surreal".
Peanut butter and baked onions don't go together.
It was typical of many of the household recipes.
As never before or since, household economists - including Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - were pushing the country's eating habits in this way.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged women to become "budget politicians" and to meet the challenge of turning pumpkin into delicious meals like creamy spaghetti and carrots.
A Square Meal is a celebration of historic treats.
Particularly delightful are the reports on the government's response to the starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's "Let Me Have Cake" attitude.
While publicly praising the simple Iowa farmhouse cuisine of his kitchen, he ate like the millionaire man of the world he had become.
"He liked continental cuisine like fish with cucumber sauce", said Coe.
He was eating in a nearly gilded dining room and wearing a tuxedo.
He was a wonderful stranger to reality.
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife Eleanor hadn't urged him to make an example of his stomach.
As the book describes, Mrs. Roosevelt's hiring of a housekeeper with no interest in taste led to the White House producing the most boring meal in Washington, but also one of the most desolate cooked".
Many of the Great Depression-era ways of dealing with food were abandoned as the country got back on its feet.
The legacy is in our continued focus on calories and food, Ziegelman said, as well as how science has been applied to food.
The couple said that when they wrote the book, they had a better understanding of Ziegelman's mother-in-law's eating habits - for example, how she could not throw away food.
"She had a real fear of food waste", said Coe.
Ziegelman remembered, "She actually made people sick".
That's when the windbag incident happened.
After the plates were cleared at Eisenberg's, she and Coe pulled out a dessert they had made at home: the plum dessert that President Roosevelt ate for lunch.
