Greenland shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
Rare sight to see.
Greenland sharks usually only come to the surface in winter.
This shark was allowed back into the sea after an inspection on board the research vessel Sanna.
He was born in 1624 and is swimming across the North Atlantic at a good 1 km/h - to this day.
Greenland sharks don't have young until they're 150.
The Greenland shark swims along the bottom of the North Atlantic Ocean, reaching an average of just 4,200 feet [1,220 m] in one hour.
Only when it counts does the five-meter-long animal accelerate to a whopping two miles per hour - half the speed of a seal at its top speed.
But this slow-paced lifestyle seems to be a recipe for old age.
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal Science that a Greenland shark may be 392 years old.
"It's crazy", says Alexander Scheuerlein of the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock, Germany, about this life span, which is a world record for vertebrates.
True, evolutionary biologists have long suspected that Greenland sharks are going to become petrified.
Just the evidence was missing.
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe, for they live mainly in the icy sea off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway, and Spitsbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures of about six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in winter.
Researchers know little about the lifestyle of Greenland sharks.
They measured their time-lapse speed when they equipped six animals with a transmitter outside Spitsbergen.
Researchers found the remains of a seal in the stomach of one of these sharks, and another had swallowed the jawbone of a young polar bear.
They may hunt sleeping animals or patrol the bottom of the sea ice, looking for corpses that are drifting down from higher water.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues now studied 28 Greenland sharks that fishermen caught off Greenland or Spitsbergen as bycatch from the depths of the North Atlantic between 2010 and 2013.
The smallest shark was just two feet [81 cm] long, while the largest was three feet [502 cm].
To determine the age of the animals, they used the carbon-14 method to analyze the lens sinks of the sharks.
This centre of the eye lens is formed before the shark is born, and the proteins contained in it are not renewed later.
The two smallest sharks had a remarkable amount of carbon-14 in their lens core.
Their birth would therefore be after the early 1960's, when nuclear weapons tests released large quantities of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
The third-smallest animal, measuring 220 centimeters (220 inches) in length, had a small surplus of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons testing, so it would have celebrated its 50th birthday in 2012 when it was examined.
All the larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had normal levels of carbon-14 in their lens cores, which is produced by cosmic radiation in the atmosphere.
In fact, the carbon-14 clock showed a 493-centimeter-long Greenland shark to be 335 years old, while the record-breaking 502-centimeter shark may even be 392 years old.
It was known that female Greenland sharks would not produce young until they were over four meters long.
Now researchers could assign length to age.
Since one of the animals, measuring some three feet [392 cm], was on the verge of maturing and was aged 156 years, it seems that the Greenland sharks take at least a century and a half to reproduce.
This is also likely to be a world record for vertebrates.
It is no coincidence that such methusulas live mainly in icy waters.
The previous record-holder, a 211-year-old Greenland whale with a 120-year-old harpoon tip stuck to its neck, was also caught off Alaska.
The low temperatures often make the organism of the animals living there run amok.
So they mature later and age more slowly.
To keep warm in the cold water, the animals often grow particularly large.
Because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
The heat loss of a gram of mouse is therefore much greater than that of a gram of elephant.
Another advantage is that you have fewer enemies.
"A smaller animal is therefore more dangerous and should focus on having as many offspring as possible as soon as possible", explains evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should invest its resources in a long life.
