NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus was probably once habitable, according to projections from a new NASA climate model.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to discover the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and carbon-dense atmosphere, could have once had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' slow rotation could be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and yet it was slowly spinning.
The model also shed light on the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had more dry areas than Earth, but once had enough water and geographical variability to support life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent matter.
"In the GISS model simulation, Venus' slow rotation exposes its day side to the sun for almost two months", explained GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release.
This heats up the surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that act as an umbrella to shield the surface from much of the sun's heat.
The result is average temperatures several degrees cooler than the Earth is today.
The model produced a story of Venus that resembled the evolution previously suspected by planetary scientists.
Although it was once probably habitable, Venus was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light over the course of several billion years.
Their oceans evaporated and their water vapor was burned away by ultraviolet light.
When their hydrogen escaped, all that was left was a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect -- Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the Geophysical Research Letters.
