Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades
The latest Kepler mission has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of rotation rates among the stars in the Pleiades.
The new data help astronomers to understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different rates and how the rotation times are related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we can learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system", said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a press release.
The Pleiades star cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this cluster, which formed about 125 million years ago, are now reaching adulthood.
They're spinning fastest now.
At peak rotation rates, these maturing stars are spewing out large amounts of stellar winds.
Since these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
When a star ages, its rotation rate starts to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by detecting the time between the appearance of a visible star spot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars spinning pirouettes more slowly than smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars", said Rebull.
Because the Pleiades are so close, they serve as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The Pleiades star cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older", said Rebull.
There is much more to learn, such as how, when, and why stars slow their rotation rates and hang their "dancing shoes", as it were.
Rebull and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades in three newspaper reports, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
