How treacherous hackers are extorting ransom
Extortion malware developers are now targeting companies - and are succeeding.
According to a recent survey of 540 companies in North America, the United Kingdom, and Germany by malware-defense specialist Malwarebytes, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been victims of an extortion-software attack at least once, or several times, in the past 12 months.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have been the target of ransomware extortion.
Forty percent of the victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the perpetrators to regain access to the compromised systems and data.
Malwarebytes' observations show that the perpetrators specialize their extortion software in increasing attacks on corporate networks.
If they succeed, the potential ransom to be extorted is significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently seeing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware", explains Marcin Kleczynski, head of Malwarebytes, in an interview with "Welt".
In 2008, most malware was still designed to send ads.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
Initially, the target was private users, but the shift to corporate attacks has been alarmingly rapid in recent months.
Ransomware works in a simple way: Once active on a victim's computer, it searches for recently modified files, such as Word, Excel, or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files encrypt the ransomware and permanently erase the originals.
The software then presents the demands of the blackmailer.
To obtain the final encryption code for the files, victims must transfer money - usually in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But whereas private users have their personal photo database at stake, companies have sensitive customer data or project databases without which production is stalled.
This means that the damage is higher when ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported losses in revenue due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely shut down their business, and in one case people's lives were in danger.
In Germany, hospitals have already been the victims of attacks on several occasions, where patients may be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always tell victims not to pay, you're only adding to the problem", Kleczynski explains.
But 80 to 90 percent of the companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to refuse the perpetrators' demands in the face of a shutdown in the company.
Hackers know this and will do anything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, F-Secure security researchers looked at the user interfaces and the contact with the blackmailers and found that the perpetrators are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to make more money.
They chat their victims about how to pay with Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites, or decrypt sample files for free.
And when individuals are redeemed after paying a few hundred euros, some companies have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit amounts to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware extortion, hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus provider Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware in about a week".
However, it is more likely that there are three or four persons involved.
The programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software kit to the actual extortionists.
The malware kits that have been around since then were created by purchasing the malware itself, consulting, and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price of between $1,000 and $10,000.
"The package includes a customization tool to change smaller configurations, appearance and branding", says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then hire additional hackers to distribute the newly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the underground forums, buy the set from one criminal, and hire another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"Usually, the criminals then hire spammers to distribute the information", explains Wisniewski.
The risk of ransomware is now well known by many companies that are doing better to secure their data.
More than 50 percent of the IT executives in the Malwarebytes survey trust ransomware to be defended by file backup and scanning software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If encryption alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful surveillance, the perpetrators instead threaten to release sensitive data, such as customer lists or price estimates", explains Marcin Kleczynski, Malwarebytes' CEO.
This means that the potential for damage is many times greater than before, depending on the type of data.
In the future, the perpetrators could also target entirely new targets in the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat connected to the Internet under their control.
In the middle of winter, unlocking such a blocked heater could be worth a ransom for many victims.
If the perpetrators then block an entire production line in a factory instead of heating it in the future, then ransomware could become an issue in Industry 4.0 as well.
